entry.et: Middle English, from Old English & Anglo-French; Old English tempel & Anglo-French temple, both from Latin templum space marked out for observation of auguries, temple, small timber; probably akin to Greek temenos sacred precinct, temnein to cut tome

def.dt: :either of two successive national sanctuaries in ancient Jerusalem
:the house of worship of Reform and some Conservative Jewish congregations
:a local lodge of any of various fraternal orders
:a place devoted to a special purpose a temple of cuisine

entry.et: Middle English, from Anglo-French, from Vulgar Latin *tempula, alteration of Latin tempora (plural) temples

def.dt: :the flattened space on each side of the forehead of some mammals including humans
:one of the side supports of a pair of glasses jointed to the bows and passing on each side of the head
